The Mistral Instruct v0.3 format uses `[INST]`/`[/INST]` markers, prepends system messages to the first user turn (separated by `\n\n`), and appends `</s>` after assistant turns. It does **not** use `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]` (unlike Ministral 3 / v7) or `[AVAILABLE_TOOLS]` (unlike v3/v3-tekken). Currently, templates in this format fall through to the differential autoparser. This change adds a dedicated specialized handler for more predictable parsing.

Constraint: Only add new code. Do not modify existing handler function bodies or `src/llama-chat.h`.

## Files to Modify

- **`common/chat.cpp`** — Add handler function + detection branch
- **`tests/test-chat-template.cpp`** — Add test case

## Step 1: Add Handler Function to `common/chat.cpp`

**Insert after line 1517** (end of `common_chat_params_init_gigachat_v3`), before `namespace workaround` at line 1519.

```cpp
static common_chat_params common_chat_params_init_mistral_instruct_v3(
        const common_chat_template &          tmpl,
        const autoparser::generation_params & inputs) {
    common_chat_params data;

    data.prompt            = common_chat_template_direct_apply_impl(tmpl, inputs);
    data.format            = COMMON_CHAT_FORMAT_PEG_NATIVE;
    data.supports_thinking = false;

    auto parser = build_chat_peg_parser([&inputs](common_chat_peg_builder & p) {
        return p.literal(inputs.generation_prompt) + p.content(p.rest());
    });

    data.parser = parser.save();

    return data;
}
```

This handler:
- Renders the prompt via `common_chat_template_direct_apply_impl()` (standard Jinja application)
- Uses `COMMON_CHAT_FORMAT_PEG_NATIVE` (same as all specialized handlers)
- Builds a minimal PEG parser: match the generation prompt literal, then capture everything as content
- No tool support, no reasoning/thinking tags, no grammar triggers (the format has no tool markers)

Pattern reference: follows the content-only path in `common_chat_params_init_gigachat_v3` (line 1489-1493).

## Step 2: Add Detection Branch in `common_chat_try_specialized_template()`

**Insert after line 1644** (closing `}` of the Ministral 3 block), before the GPT-OSS comment at line 1646.

```cpp
    // Mistral Instruct v0.3 - simple [INST]/[/INST] format, system prepended to first user turn
    // Distinguishes from Ministral 3/v7 (have [SYSTEM_PROMPT]) and v3/v3-tekken (have [AVAILABLE_TOOLS])
    if (src.find("' [INST] '") != std::string::npos &&
        src.find("[SYSTEM_PROMPT]") == std::string::npos &&
        src.find("[AVAILABLE_TOOLS]") == std::string::npos) {
        LOG_DBG("Using specialized template: Mistral Instruct v0.3\n");
        return common_chat_params_init_mistral_instruct_v3(tmpl, params);
    }
```

Detection rationale:
- **`' [INST] '` present** — The Jinja string literal `' [INST] '` (with leading space, in single quotes) appears in v0.3/v1-style templates. Distinguishes from v0.2 (`'[INST] '`, no leading space), v3/tekken (`"[INST] "`, double quotes), and llama2 (`<<SYS>>`/`[INST]` without single-quoted Jinja strings).
- **`[SYSTEM_PROMPT]` absent** — Excludes v7 and Ministral 3 templates.
- **`[AVAILABLE_TOOLS]` absent** — Excludes v3 and v3-tekken templates.

No false positives among the 50+ existing test cases or model templates.

